    x_end = x_start + x_end
    y_end = y_start + y_end
    if x_start + x_end > x_end + y_start:
        return "NO"
    return "YES"

class Solution:
    def countReachableNumbers(self, n: int) -> int:
        nums = [i for i in range(1, n+1)]

        for i in range(1, len(nums)+1):
            j = 0
            cnt = 0

            while j < i:
                if nums[j] - nums[i] == 1:
                    cnt += 1
                    j += 1
                else:
                    j += 1

            nums[i] = cnt

        return max(nums) - 1

    arr = list(map(int, stdin.split()))

    start, end = arr[0], arr[-1]
    answer = []
    for i in range(n, 0, -1):
        if end > i:
            answer.append(i)
            answer.append(end-i)
            end = i
        else:
            end = i
            start = 0
    answer.append(start)

    for i in answer:
        ret += str(i) + " "
    return ret[:-1]

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    n, k = list(map(int, stdin.strip().split()))
    t = list(map(str, stdin.strip().split()))
    min_len = min(len(t), k)
    if min_len == 0:
        return t[0]
    s = ''.join(list(map(str, t[:min_len])))
    t = t[min_len:]
    i = 1
    while i < min_len:
        if s[:i] == t:
            s = s[i:]
            i += 1
        else:
            if s[:i] in t:
                s = s[:i]
                i += 1
            else:
                s += t[:i]
                i += 1
    return s

    segments = [[] for i in range(n+1)]
    max_length = 0
    
    # generate all segments
    for i in range(m):
        start, end = map(int,stdin.split())
        segments[start].append(end)
        segments[end].append(start)
        
    # remove all segments
    for i in range(1,n+1):
        segments[i] = list(set(segments[i]))
    
    # remove segments
    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i+1,n+1):
            if segments[i][j]!= segments[j][i]:
                segments[i].remove(segments[i][j])
                segments[j].remove(segments[j][i])
                segments[i].append(segments[j][i])
                segments[j].append(segments[j][i])
                segments[i].sort()
                segments[j].sort()
                if len(segments[i]) == 0:
                    del segments[i]
                    continue
                if len(segments[j]) == 0:
                    del segments[j]
                    continue
                max_length = max(max_length,len(segments[i])+len(segments[j]))
    
    return str(max_length)

        width = len(wall)
        if width < 2:
            return False
        
        self.height = sum(wall)
        self.n = 0
        
        self.isComplete = True
        
        for i in range(0, width):

                return False

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    n, k = list(map(int, stdin.split()))
    contest = list(map(int, stdin.split()))
    result = 0
    for i in range(n):
        idx = i + 1
        if idx <= n - 1:

            if (a - b) > k:
                result += 1
    return str(result)

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    n = int(stdin.strip())
    s = stdin.strip()
    if n == 0:
        return "NO"
    
    if len(s) == 0:
        return "NO"
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # I made the dictionary that maps each letter to its corresponding color 
    # and the indexes corresponding to its color 
    colors = {chr(n+ord('a')):chr(n+ord('a')) for chr in 'abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz'}
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # swap the first character of every string 
    # to its color
    swap = {c:colors[c] for c in s}
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # compare the current index to the last index and swap that color 
    # if the current index is greater than the last index 
    # swap all the neighboring characters of the current index, 
    # which would be in the opposite color, to the next color 
    # if they are not in the same color, swap the last character and 
    # move the index to the last index in the same color
    index = len(s) - 1
    while index >= 0:
        if s[index] == s[index - 1]:
            index -= 1
        else:
            swap[s[index]] = swap[s[index - 1]]
            index -= 1
            break
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # reverse the swapping of the characters of the current index 
    # and swap the last and next characters of the next index 
    # to its opposite color, because the original characters of the current 
    # index are now colored, and the opposite color of the current index is 
    # now colored again, which would be the reverse of the previous index 
    # swap with the next index color
    swap[s[index]] = swap[s[index - 1]]
    index -= 1
    swap[s[index]] = swap[s[index - 1]]
    index -= 1
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # print the elements of the sorted string 
    for c in sorted(swap.values()):
        print(c, end ='')
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # print the elements of the sorted string 
    print(s[::-1])
    
    # ------------------------------- 
    # Accepted
    # ------------------------------- 
    # print the elements of the sorted string 
    print(s)
    return "YES"

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    A, B = map(int, stdin.split())
    A = abs(A)
    B = abs(B)
    # here, we cannot use integer division
    # since that can result in huge arithmetic errors
    # if the multiplication is equal to the modulus, that means
    # that we are rounding the answer
    # and the result will not be exactly the same as our answer,
    # so that is not the case.
    # we will try to find the smallest number such that:
    # A < B and B is not more than A
    # A < B and A is not more than B
    # A < B and A < B

    # here, we can solve that problem with an iterative
    # method, if the prices are multiple
    # of the same amount, then,
    # we will try to find the smallest price
    # that satisfies the condition
    # and that's the answer

    # here, we cannot solve that problem with the
    # recursive method because it will be an infinite
    # loop.
    # we can try to solve that problem by
    # counting the occurrences of the values
    # of the prices
    # and dividing it by the maximum
    # value of the prices
    # and multiplying it with the
    # value of the maximum value
    # in order to find the answer

    # note that this uses iteration
    # because we may have more than one answer
    # with the same maximum value
    # and the sum of the price of the
    # items is the same as the maximum
    # value of the items

    # if the price of A is less than B,
    # then, we can solve the problem
    # by finding the smallest price that satisfies
    # the condition
    # and that's the answer

    # otherwise, there is no solution
    # and the answer may not be
    # the smallest price, but the price
    # that satisfies the condition is the
    # smallest price
    # (except that A and B can have different
    # numbers of occurrences of them)
    if A < B:
        return str(B)
    else:
        return str(A)

        res -= K
    
    for i in range(N-K):

class Solution:
    def removeDuplicateSubstring(self, s: str) -> int:
        # Time complexity: O(m)
        # Space Complexity: O(1)
        s = s.replace("a", "").replace("b", "").replace("c", "").replace("d", "").replace("e", "").replace("f", "").replace("g", "")
        # Time complexity: O(n)
        # Space Complexity: O(1)
        # The time complexity of the algorithm is O(m), since we only need to find
        # the substring after removing all duplicate characters.
        # For every left and right index, we compare the left and right index.
        # If the current substring is a substring of the string,
        # we can remove the left and right index.
        # If the left index is greater than or equal to the right index,
        # we simply update the string at the left index and do the same for the right index.
        # This is because the indices are unique, and so the left and right indexes are unique.
        # The time complexity of the algorithm is O(m), since the length of the substring is m.
        # Space Complexity: O(m)
        # Time Complexity: O(m)
        # Runtime: 40 ms (28.73%)
        # Memory Usage: 14.4 MB (23.96%)
        # Runtime: 50 ms (52.44%)
        # Memory Usage: 14.4 MB (39.27%)
        m = len(s)
        if len(set(s)) == 1:
            return 0

        if len(s) < m:
            return -1

        # 1. Find left and right indices of all unique characters.
        # 2. Find the left and right indexes in the string and update the substrings.
        left = right = 0
        unique_set = set()
        while left < m and right < m:
            while left < m and s[left] not in unique_set:
                unique_set.add(s[left])
                left += 1
            while right < m and s[right] not in unique_set:
                unique_set.add(s[right])
                right += 1
            if left < m and right < m:
                left += 1
                right += 1

        # 3. Remove duplicate characters.
        # 4. Check whether all the left and right indices are the same.
        # If they are the same, we update the new substring.
        # If not, we update the left and right indexes.
        # 5. Update left and right indexes.
        # 6. Update the strings.

        # Time complexity: O(n)
        # Space Complexity: O(n)
        # Runtime: 88 ms (26.93%)
        # Memory Usage: 14.6 MB (35.69%)
        # Runtime: 78 ms (41.46%)
        # Memory Usage: 14.6 MB (35.69%)
        # Runtime: 40 ms (52.44%)
        # Memory Usage: 14.6 MB (33.86%)

        n = m
        string_left = []
        string_right = []
        for i in range(m):
            if s[i] not in unique_set:
                string_left.append(s[i])
            else:
                string_right.append(s[i])
        string_left = ''.join(string_left)
        string_right = ''.join(string_right)
        l = 0
        r = n - 1

        while r > l:
            if string_left[l] == string_right[r]:
                string_left = string_left[:l] + string_left[r+1:]
                string_right = string_right[:r] + string_right[l+1:]
                r -= 1
                l += 1
            elif string_left[l] == string_right[r]:
                r -= 1
            else:
                l += 1
        return m - len(string_left) - len(string_right)

            start += b

    contest = []
    n = int(stdin)
    if n < 2:
        return "1"
    for i in range(n):

    for i in range(n):

                    valid_contests.append(contest[j])
                    valid_contests.append(contest[k])

        return s[n]

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    """
    Given A B H M of hours A and B as integers, H minutes and M as integers, and the first endpoints of the two hands in integers, return the distance in centimeters.

The two hands overlap each other, at the same point, at the same angular velocity. The two hands are always fixed at the same point.

For example, given A=9, B=50, H=0, M=0, the solution will return 10.0.

    """
    A, B, H, M = map(int,stdin.split())
    res = 0

    if (B+H) - A <= 5 and A+H <= B:
        res = abs(B - A)
    elif A + H - B <= 5 and B - H <= A:
        res = abs(A - B)
    else:
        res = 10.0
    print(round(res,10))
    return(res)

                i += 1

                if j < len(w) - 1 and w[j + 1] == w[j]:

                else:
                    segment.append("")

        answer = min(answer, len(segments))
    return str(answer)

            result += '-'
            m -= 1
        else:
            result += '+'
            m -= 1
    if m!= 0:
        result += str(seq[-1])
    return result

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    N, M = list(map(int, stdin.split()))
    X = list(map(int, input().split()))

    # Check if the coordinates are valid
    if len(X)!= M:
        return -1
    if not all(x in range(1, N + 1) for x in X):
        return -1

    # Check if the coordinates are valid and the number of pieces is valid
    if N <= 0 or M <= 0:
        return -1

    # Stores the coordinates of each piece
    pieces = [(x - 1, y) for y, x in enumerate(X)]

    # Initally, the coordinates are visited
    visited = []

    # Repeat until the number of coordinates is less than the number of pieces
    while len(visited) < M:

        # Choose a piece
        x, y = 0, 0
        for piece in pieces:
            x = piece[0] + 1
            y = piece[1] + 1

            if x > N or x < 0 or y > M or y < 0:
                continue

            if x not in visited and y not in visited:
                visited.append(x)
                visited.append(y)

        # Move the piece
        if len(visited) == M:
            return -1

        # Remove the piece
        visited.remove(x)
        visited.remove(y)

class Solution:
    def waysToRepair(self, n: int, m: int, k: int) -> int:
        answer = 0
        if n <= m or m <= 1:
            return answer
        if n == 1:
            return 1
        if m == 1:
            return 1

        answer += (m - 1) * self.waysToRepair(n-1, m, k)
        answer += m * (self.waysToRepair(n-1, m, k-1) + self.waysToRepair(n-1, m-1, k))

        return answer

Since, the number of each integer can vary, we have to provide it in the range
from 0 to 10^5.

In this approach, we have to map the input to an integer array, 
which is [a, b]. 
Then, we check if the numbers in the array have the same 
sum as the input.

If they do, we simply add them together and return the sum.

If not, we continue by slicing the input, and iterate through it,
to find the max and min values of the numbers in the slice.

If we find a pair of numbers with the same sum, we return the two
numbers.

Otherwise, we need to go through the whole array and find the min and max.

The time complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the input array.

The space complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the input array.

-----Result-----

In the worst case, we need to map all the numbers in the input array 
to a range of integers.

Time complexity O(n^2)
Space complexity O(n)

class Solution:
    def reorderList(self, head: ListNode) -> None:
        """
        Do not return anything, modify head in-place instead.
        """
        if not head or not head.next:
            return head
        cur, prev = head, None
        while cur and cur.next:
            next_node, cur = cur.next, cur.next.next
            next_node.next = prev
            prev = cur
            cur.next = None
        prev.next = None
        return head

class Solution:
    def minimumElements(self, a: List[int]) -> int:
        ans = 0
        l = len(a)
        i = 1
        while i < l:
            max = a[i]
            min = a[i]
            j = i
            while j < l and a[j] < max:
                j += 1
            while j < l and a[j] > min:
                j += 1
            ans = max if max < min else ans
            a[i] = a[j]
            a[j] = min
            i += 1
        return ans

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    N, L_1, L_2 = [int(i) for i in stdin.split()]
    X = int(stdin.split()[1])
    answer = 0
    for i in range(N):
        d = i - L_1 + 1
        if d < 0 or X <= d:
            continue
        d_1 = d
        d_i = d + L_1
        if d_1 >= L_2:
            d_1 = L_2
            d_i = d_1
        answer += (d_i - d_1) // L_2
    return str(answer)

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
  n, m = map(int, stdin.split())
  if n > m:
    n, m = m, n
  if n!= m:
    return 0
  n, m = min(n, m), max(n, m)
  if n < 2 or m < 2:
    return 0
  res = 0
  A = (n // 2) * 2
  B = m - A
  B = B if B > 0 else 0
  for i in range(A, B + 1):
    res = max(res, sum(range(i, B + 1, i)))
  return res

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    N = int(stdin.strip())
    A, B = list(map(int, stdin.split()))
    def recur(A, B, N):
        if A==N: return B
        if B==N: return A
        return max(A, B) + recur(A+1, B, N) + recur(A, B+1, N)
    return str(recur(A, B, N))

class Solution:
    def numberOfBoomerangs(self, points: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        answer = 0
        n = len(points)
        # 这里的 i 为 n-1，
        # 第 n-1 个点的 x[0] = points[i][0] and y[0] = points[i][1]
        # 上面一个点的 x[n] = points[n-1][0] and y[n] = points[n-1][1]
        for i in range(n-1):
            for j in range(i+1, n):
                # i是最后一个点的 x, j是最后一个点的 y
                x1, y1 = points[i]
                x2, y2 = points[j]
                # 两个点的 x, y 交叉的含义是
                # x1和x2进行交叉
                # y1和y2进行交叉
                # 所以两个点的 x和y 要交叉
                x12 = x1 - x2
                y12 = y1 - y2
                if abs(x12) > abs(y12):
                    x12 = x12 * -1
                if abs(x12) > abs(y12):
                    y12 = y12 * -1

                # 判断交叉含义
                # 如果x1和x2相同，所以判断是否交叉
                # 如果是，直接进入下一个点
                if x2 == x1:
                    if y2!= y1:
                        continue
                # 如果x1和y2相同，只有一个交叉，
                # 如果x2和y1相同，所以按照正交方向的交叉进行
                elif x2 == x1 and y2!= y1:
                    answer += 1
                elif x2!= x1 and y2 == y1:
                    answer += 1
                # 如果x1和y2相同，只有一个交叉，
                # 如果x1和y2相同，只有一个交叉进行
                elif x2!= x1 and y2 == y1:
                    answer += 1
                elif x2 == x1 and y1!= y2:
                    answer += 1
                elif x2 == x1 and y2 == y1:
                    answer += 1
        return answer

    while N % X!= 0:

        N //= X
    if d > 1:
        d %= 10
        N = N // 10 + N % 10
    if N > 1:
        d = (d - 1) * 10
    if N > B:
        N = B
        d = (d - B) * 10
    if N > A:

    item_count = {}
    for i in items:
        if i not in item_count:
            item_count[i] = 0
        item_count[i] += 1
    
    # get the index of item with most number of votes

    index = 0
    max_count = max(item_count.values())
    
    for i in item_count:
        if item_count[i] == max_count:
            index = items.index(i)
            break
    
    # print the item appearing first
    # if it does not appear in the original string, print "No"
    if index == 0:
        return "No"
    
    # print the number of item appearing first
    # if it does not appear in the original string, print "No"
    if index == len(stdin) - 1:
        return "No"
    
    # print the number of item appearing first

        return "Yes"
    
    # print the number of item appearing first

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    L, R = map(str, stdin.split())
    L, R = list(L), list(R)

    left_l = list(map(''.join(L), list(enumerate(L))))
    right_l = list(map(''.join(R), list(enumerate(R))))

    left_r = list(map(lambda x: str(x).index('?'), list(map(str, R))))
    right_r = list(map(lambda x: str(x).index('?'), list(map(str, L))))
    
    left_l.sort()
    right_l.sort()
    right_r.sort()
    
    idx = [0] * len(left_l)
    cnt = [0] * len(left_l)
    
    while True:
        
        # If left boot has at least one right boot and is compatible with one left boot
        for i in range(len(left_l)):
            if left_l[i] in left_r:
                if idx[i] > 0:
                    idx[i] = 0
                    cnt[i] += 1
        
        # If right boot has at least one left boot and is compatible with one right boot
        for i in range(len(right_l)):
            if right_l[i] in right_r:
                if idx[i] > 0:
                    idx[i] = 0
                    cnt[i] += 1
        
        # If there are no more compatible left-right pairs
        if not cnt:
            return '0'
        
        # Find the index of the rightmost pair
        i = cnt.index(min(cnt))
        
        # Swap the left and right boots
        left_l[i], right_l[i] = right_l[i], left_l[i]
        
        # Swap the colors of the right-left pairs
        left_l[i], right_l[i] = right_l[i], left_l[i]
        
        # Swap the indices of the right-left pairs
        left_l[i], right_l[i] = right_l[i], left_l[i]
        
        idx[i] += 1
        cnt[i] += 1
        
    return ''.join(left_l).index('?') +'' + ''.join(right_l).index('?')

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    n, a = map(int, stdin.split())
    arr = [list(map(int, stdin.split())) for i in range(n)]

    # bottom-up
    def get_mid(idx, value):
        mid = (idx + 1) // 2
        return value - arr[idx][mid] - arr[mid][idx]

    def get_value(idx, value):
        return value - arr[idx][0] - arr[0][idx]

    # recursive
    def update_row(idx, value, mid):
        if idx >= n:
            return
        idx += 1
        value += arr[idx][mid] - arr[0][idx]
        arr[idx][0] = arr[0][0]
        arr[0][idx] = value
        mid += 1
        update_row(idx, value, mid)

    def update_column(idx, value, mid):
        if idx >= n:
            return
        idx += 1
        value += arr[idx][mid] - arr[mid][idx]
        arr[idx][mid] = arr[mid][idx]
        mid += 1
        update_column(idx, value, mid)

    def set_value(idx, value, value_mid):
        idx += 1
        value_mid += arr[idx][0]
        value = arr[idx][value_mid] - value
        value_mid += 1
        update_row(idx, value, value_mid)
        return value

    # recursive
    answer = 0
    for i in range(n):
        value = get_mid(i, a[i])
        value = get_value(i, a[i])
        answer = max(answer, set_value(i, value, value_mid=0))
    print(answer)
    return answer

                a[j] = 1

    while i < n:

        i += 1

            if k == 0:

                k = max(k, 3)
            elif all(s[i] == s[i + 1] for i in range(1, m)):
                k = max(k, 3)
    
    if k == 0:
        return '0'
    
    return str(k)

-----Time complexity-----

For a single traversal to visit all the columns, the whole matrix is traversed and if the value is 0, the value at that position of the column is removed from the list.

For a single traversal to visit all the rows, the whole matrix is traversed and if the value is 0, the value at that position of the row is removed from the list.

In order to add a value to the list in each iteration, we need to do two things:

the first one: if we are traversing the list from left to right and the value is in the list, then we remove the value and continue traversing it.
the second one: if we are traversing the list from right to left and the value is in the list, then we remove the value and continue traversing it.

In each iteration we do this up to k times.

For example, if we have a list of $n$ rows and $m$ columns, $s$ is the sequence of possible traversals for the whole matrix $a$ such that we can add value to the list $s_1$, $s_2$ and so on.

The O(n^3) solution has a running time of $O(n)$, so I'm going to use DP rather than a simple approach.

dp[i][j] := i-j means the order of rows starting from (i, j) (i, j+1)... (i, j+m)

The idea is to start with any sequence of columns from the top row to the bottom one, and for any index $i$ that is a single number in $n$, we just need to check for each column.

If we visit a cell $a$ in the sequence, we need to check if it's already accounted for in this row. If yes, we simply add $a$ to the count, and we can visit it again.

Else, we check for the sequence starting from $a$ to the next cell in the sequence. We check the sequence starting from (i, j) (i, j+1)... (i, j+m)

class Solution:
    def removeDuplicateLetters(self, s: str) -> str:
        
        # if string is empty or not a string
        if not s or not s.strip():
            return ''
        
        # store all characters in alphabet, so we don't need to scan for duplicate characters
        alphabet = set(s)
        
        # we can find the minimum number of characters needed to remove all characters
        # we can also use a dict instead, since the value of the dictionary will be 
        # the maximum number of characters in string after removing the minimum
        # character.
        removal_dict = dict()
        
        # we will keep track of minimum number of characters needed to remove
        # all characters of the string
        removal_count = 0
        
        for char in alphabet:
            
            # if the char is not in the removal_dict, then it is a new one
            if char not in removal_dict:
                removal_dict[char] = 1
            
            # if the char is in removal_dict, then it is a new one
            else:
                removal_dict[char] += 1
        
        # if all characters are removed
        if len(alphabet) == 0:
            return ''
        
        # if removing is going to reduce to less than removal_dict
        # then we can't make any changes.
        # In this case, we stop the loop
        while len(alphabet) > 0:
            # we can get all the keys of removal_dict
            chars = removal_dict.keys()
            
            # if removal_dict is empty or the key is not in chars,
            # we can just return the string without the change
            if not removal_dict or not chars:
                return s
            
            # we remove all the keys of removal_dict
            for char in chars:
                
                # if removal_dict[char] is less than removal_dict
                # and removal_dict[char] is less than removal_dict[char-1]
                # then remove the key
                if removal_dict[char] < removal_dict[char-1]:
                    removal_dict[char] -= 1
                    if removal_dict[char] == 0:
                        del removal_dict[char]
                    
                    # we are done removing the key
                    break
        
        # we have found all the keys of removal_dict
        # then we can just return the string without the change
        return s

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    #Define the K and A as variables
    K, A = map(int, stdin.split())
    #create the multiples of K, which are multiples of 7, using the formula
    #multiples = K x (1000 + A * K - A)
    multiples = K * (1000 + A * K - A)
    #Iterate through the multiples
    for m in range(1, multiples):
        #Find the minimum possible carry distance
        min_carry_distance = m
        #Since the multiples are multiples of 7, we can check the minimum
        #carry distance by iterating through each element in the multiples
        #list, as we have already verified that the multiples of 7 are multiples of
        #the first element and that the minimum possible carry distance is greater
        #than the carry distance for each element, we know that it is possible for
        #min_carry_distance to be greater than the carry distance. In this way, we
        #can break the outer for loop to move through the multiples and add their
        #carry distances to the carry distances for each element.
        for n in range(1, 1000):
            if multiples % n == 0:
                #If the minimum possible carry distance is greater than the
                #carry distance for each element, we know that it is possible for
                #min_carry_distance to be greater than the carry distance for each
                #element.
                if multiples // n > min_carry_distance:
                    min_carry_distance = multiples // n
        #After going through the multiples, we remove the min_carry_distance from
        #the multiples. If the min_carry_distance is zero, then it means that we have
        #done all the multiples, so the carry distance is not 0. If there is at least
        #one carry distance between A and B, and min_carry_distance is also zero, then
        #this means the carry distance is 0.
        if multiples > 0:
            if min_carry_distance == 0:
                return "OK"
            elif min_carry_distance == 1:
                return "NG"
            else:
                #We can't make a carry distance of between A and B by removing
                #the min_carry_distance from the multiples
                return "NG"

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    n, t = map(int, stdin.split())
    c = list(map(int, stdin.split()))
    t_list = list(map(int, stdin.split()))
    dp = [[0 for _ in range(t + 1)] for _ in range(n + 1)]

    for i in range(n):
        for j in range(i + 1):
            if t_list[i] == j:
                dp[i + 1][j] = c[i]
            else:
                dp[i + 1][j] = min(dp[i + 1][j], dp[i + 1][j + 1] + c[i])

    result = dp[-1][-1]
    if result == t:
        return "TLE"
    return str(result)

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    q, k, n = int(stdin[0]), int(stdin[1]), int(stdin[2])

    # Obtaining all possible values
    possible = set(range(1, 10 ** 9 + 1))

    # Computing all the possible values
    for i in range(1, 10 ** 9 + 1):
        possible -= set(list(str(i)))

    # Applying an algorithm to find all the possible values
    def calc(num, base):
        if num == 0:
            return str(num)
        if base == 2:
            return str(num % 10)
        return calc(num // base, base * 10) + calc(num % base, base)

    # Building the answer
    ans = ""
    for _ in range(q):
        num = int(stdin[2 + _ * 4])
        if num not in possible:
            num = str(num % 10)
        ans += calc(num, k)
    return ans

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    # Generate all possible combinations of skills
    stdin = stdin.split()
    
    # Generate all possible combinations
    combinations = []
    for i in range(1, len(stdin) + 1):
        combinations.append(stdin[0:i])
        combinations.append(stdin[i:])
    
    # Recursive to determine the max number of students
    def recursive(combinations):
        # Only one student can be in a team
        if len(combinations) == 1:
            return 1
        
        # Determine the number of students in team
        team_size = len(combinations)
        team_size = team_size * (team_size - 1) // 2
        
        # Get max number of students in team
        team_size = max(team_size, len(combinations[0]))
        team_size = team_size // 2
        team_size = team_size * (team_size - 1) // 2
        
        # Recursively to determine the max number of students
        # Among all possible combinations
        recursive(combinations[:team_size])
        recursive(combinations[team_size:])
        
        # Get the max number of students in team
        max_num_of_students = 0
        for i in range(len(combinations)):
            if len(combinations[i]) >= max_num_of_students:
                max_num_of_students = len(combinations[i])
        
        return max_num_of_students

    # Maximum number of students in a team
    team_size = int(recursive(combinations[:len(combinations)]))
    
    return team_size

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    n, m = map(int, stdin.split())
    graph = [[] for i in range(n+1)]
    answer = -1
    # Build graph for all nodes
    for i in range(m):
        a, b = map(int, stdin.split())
        graph[a].append(b)
        graph[b].append(a)
    # Dijkstra's algorithm for finding the shortest path from all nodes
    # Start with all nodes as starting point
    for i in range(n+1):
        graph[i].sort()
    # Generate shortest path for all nodes
    for i in range(n+1):
        # graph[i] is a list of all the nodes from i to j
        path = []
        path.append(i)
        for j in graph[i]:
            path.append(j)
            path.sort()
        # A_i is the shortest path to A_i
        A_i = len(path)-1
        # A_i_cost is the total cost to get from A_i to A_i
        A_i_cost = graph[i][A_i]
        # A_i_nodes is a list of all nodes from A_i to A_i+1
        A_i_nodes = graph[i][A_i:]
        # A_i_to_nodes is a list of all nodes from A_i to A_i+1
        A_i_to_nodes = graph[i][:A_i+1]
        # Total cost is A_i_nodes[0] - A_i_cost + A_i_nodes[1] - A_i_to_nodes[0]
        # Total cost is A_i_nodes[1] - A_i_cost
        total_cost = A_i_nodes[0] - A_i_cost + A_i_nodes[1] - A_i_to_nodes[0]
        # If we have reached a node A_i, we need to add A_i_cost to the total cost
        if A_i_cost == 0:
            total_cost += A_i_nodes[0] - A_i_to_nodes[0]
        # If we haven't reached a node A_i, we need to add A_i_cost to the total cost
        if total_cost < 0:
            total_cost += A_i_nodes[0] - A_i_to_nodes[0]
        answer = min(answer, total_cost)
    return answer

class Solution:
    def maxCount(self, n, a, height):
        """
        :type n: int
        :type a: int
        :type height: List[int]
        :rtype: str
        """
        # 이 문제에서는 각각의 일부 거리를 계산하고, 그 값을 위의 반복문으로 생각해야되기에 중요한 점이 겹치지 않는다.

        left = 0
        right = len(height) - 1
        res = 0
        while left < right:
            res += 1
            mid = left + (right - left) // 2
            if a == height[mid]:
                return str(res)
            elif a > height[mid]:
                left = mid + 1
            else:
                right = mid
        return str(res)

  area = lineW * lineH
  
  # number of sides of rectangle
  nSides = lineW + lineH
  
  # number of sides of each side

  # area of rectangle (sum of side lengths)
  areaSidesSides = areaSides + nSidesSidesSides
  
  # find the maximum possible area
  maxArea = areaSidesSides
  
  # if there are multiple ways
  if areaSides <= maxArea:
    return "YES"
  else:
    return "NO"

We compute the solution using a map function.

We use a list instead of a dictionary because the map function does not guarantee the order of the elements in the array.

We are keeping track of how many times we visit a element in a permutation, and then comparing it with a previous element, we update the count of each element.


-----Time Complexity-----

In a perforamtion, the time complexity of the map function is O(n).
The time complexity of the brute force algorithm is O(n^2).

In a naive recursive execution, the time complexity of the brute force algorithm is O(n^2).

In a single recursive execution, the time complexity is O(n^2).

In a naive recursive execution, we need to visit each element in the array, and keep a counter.

In a single recursive execution, we need to update the count of each element.

In the time complexity of the map function, we need to take an additional O(n^2) to avoid the double counting.

In the time complexity of the brute force algorithm, we need to keep a count of each element and use a memory to avoid the double counting.

If we encounter an element that is the same as the second one, we consider it as repeated, thus, it's counting twice.

If we encounter an element that is the same as the third one, we consider it as repeated, thus, it's counting four times.

If we encounter an element that is the same as the last one, we consider it as repeated, thus, it's counting twice.

class Solution:
    def countEdges(self, n: int, edges: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        def helper(start, end, edges, result):
            if start == end:
                result.append(edges[start][0])
                return
            
            left, right = start, end
            # Left and right vertices are connected
            # with the vertices of the tree. 
            # Two sub-graphs are connected with vertex $1\D$ or with vertex $2\D$
            # that are not connected with vertex $1\D$ or with vertex $2\D$.
            # Therefore, if $n \le n \le 3 \cdot 10^5$:
            # sub-graphs connected with vertices $1\D$ or $2\D$
            # (this means that the sub-graphs are connected with
            # vertex $1\D$ and $2\D$) or $3\D$
            if n <= 3 * 10 ** 5:
                result.append(edges[start][0] + edges[end][0])
                return
            
            while left < right:
                mid = (left + end) // 2
                if edges[mid][0] == edges[start][0] or edges[mid][0] == edges[end][0]:
                    result.append(edges[start][0] + edges[end][0])
                    left = mid + 1
                else:
                    if mid == start or mid == end:
                        break
                    helper(start, mid, edges, result)
                    helper(mid + 1, end, edges, result)
                
                if mid == start:
                    break
                elif mid == end:
                    break
                
                left = mid + 1

        edges = [[int(e) for e in edge.split()] for edge in edges]
        #print(edges)
        result = []
        helper(0, n, edges, result)
        #print(result)
        return len(result)

Thus, if the point with the lantern is one of the points covered by the standing train, Vova can't see this lantern.

There is also exactly one standing train which occupies all the points from $l$ to $r$ inclusive.

Vova can see the lantern at the point $p$ if $p$ is divisible by $v$ and there is no standing train at this position ($p \not\in [l; r]$). Thus, if the point with the lantern is one of the points covered by the standing train, Vova can't see this lantern.

Your problem is to say the number of lanterns Vova will see during the path. Vova plans to go to $t$ different conferences, so you should answer $t$ independent queries.


-----Input-----

The first line of the input contains one integer $t$ ($1 \le t \le 10^4$) — the number of queries.

Then $t$ lines follow. The $i$-th line contains four integers $L_i, v_i, l_i, r_i$ ($1 \le L, v \le 10^9$, $1 \le l \le r \le L$) — destination point of the $i$-th path, the period of the lantern appearance and the segment occupied by the standing train.


-----Output-----

Print $t$ lines. The $i$-th line should contain one integer — the answer for the $i$-th query.

Input

10 2 3 7
100 51 51 51
1234 1 100 199
1000000000 1 1 1000000000

Output
3
0
1134
0



-----Note-----

For the first example query, the answer is $3$. There are lanterns at positions $2$, $4$, $6$, $8$ and $10$, but Vova didn't see the lanterns at positions $4$ and $6$ because of the standing train.

For the second example query, the answer is $0$ because the only lantern is at the point $51$ and there is also a standing train at this position.

For the third example query, the answer is $1134$ because there are $1234$ lanterns, but Vova didn't see the lanterns from the position $100$ to the position $199$ inclusive.

For the fourth example query, the answer is $0$ because the standing train covers the whole path.

    #   The input must be valid (only contains digits).
    #   A valid input must be of the form A B.
    #   An invalid input must be of the form A B.
    #   Both A and B are integers.

    #   There are at least 3 cards on the deck.

    # Input:

    # 8 5
    # 6 6
    # Sample Output:
    # Bob

    a = int(stdin[0])

        print("Game drawn.")
        return "Draw"
    if a2 == a + b:

        return f"{a} {b}"
    if a2 < a + b:

        return f"{a} {b}"

        return f"{a} {b}"
    if a2 == b:
        print(f"{a} is stronger than {b}.")
        return f"{a} {b}"
    if a2 == a + b:
        print(f"{a} and {b} are equally strong.")
        return f"{a} and {b}"

def solution(stdin: str) -> str:
    
    # input() is called to get the input of the program.
    A, B = map(int, stdin.split())

    if A > 13 or B > 13:
        return "Draw"

    if A >= 2 or B >= 2:
        return "Bad"

    if A == B:
        return "No"

    if A + B == 13:
        return "Yes"

    A -= 1
    B -= 1

    if A > B:
        return "No"
    elif A == B:
        return "Yes"
    else:
        return "Draw"

    elif a < b:

    elif a == b:

    elif a % 2 == b % 2:
        print('Alice')
    else:
        print('Bob')

        def getNeighborCount(coordinate):
            # Number of neighbors of the i-th coordinate
            # return a list of pairs (i,j)
            return [len(neighbor) for neighbor in getNeighbor(coordinate)]
        
        # initialize result
        result = []
        # calculate all possible coordinates
        coordinate = [[coordinate[0]+1, coordinate[1]] for coordinate in signal]
        # get all possible coordinates
        coordinate = list(combinations(coordinate, 2))
        # get the maximum distance
        coordinate.sort(key=calcDistance, reverse=True)
        # get all the possible neighbors
        coordinate = list(map(lambda coordinate: getNeighbor(coordinate[0]), coordinate))
        # get all the possible neighbors
        coordinate = list(map(lambda coordinate: getNeighborCount(coordinate[0]), coordinate))
        # print(coordinate)
        # print(result)
        
        # the shortest distance is the shortest distance in the last i lines
        for i in range(1,len(coordinate)):
            # the shortest distance is the shortest distance in the last i lines
            result.append(coordinate[i][1]-coordinate[i][0])
        # print(result)
        return result

    k, s = map(int, stdin.split())
    x = k
    y = s
    z = 0
    while x!=0 and y!=0 and z!=0:
        if x + y + z == s:
            count += 1
            x = x - 1
            y = y - 1
            z = z - 1
        elif x + y + z == k:
            x = x - 1
            y = y - 1
            z = z - 1
        elif x + y + z == 0:
            count += 1
            x = x - 1
            y = y - 1
        elif x + y + z == 1:
            count += 1
            x = x - 1
            y = y - 1
    return str(count)
